stanzas.stanza_text:
On  roof a grave assembly sate;
His roof, a refuge to the feather'd kind;
With serious look he mark'd the nice debate,
And to his  thus address'd his mind.

Thus taught, they meditate a speedy slight;
For this, ev'n now they prune their vig'rous wing;
For this, consult, advise, prepare, excite,
And prove their strength in many an airy ring.

'Tis thus life's chearful seasons roll away;
Thus threats the winter of inclement age;
Our time of action but a summer's day;
And earth's frail orb the sadly-varied stage!

Let no fond love for earth exact a sigh,
No doubts divert our steddy steps aside;
Nor let us long to live, nor dread to die;
Heav'n is our Hope, and Providence our Guide.
